online.search
Class Search_Driver

java.lang.Object
  online.search.CommonDriver
      online.search.Search_Driver
All Implemented Interfaces:
Constants, TreeProviderProtocol
public class Search_Driver
extends CommonDriver
implements Constants

this is the overall controller for a search. Although the actual structure of the search is a traditional alpha-beta driven evaluation, all the data is maintained in this class and Search_Node classes, instead of the traditional recursive stack based structure. It's less efficient this way, but much easier to control the overall progress of the search when the control thread is independent of the search state. * @author ddyer

use_nullmove

public boolean use_nullmove
if true, use a forced null move first at every turn change, and promote the best continuation of the result as a refutation of each move. For this to work, the client game has to be able to perform MOVE_NULL which is simply a turnover to the next player, even if not normally allowed. the original MAKE/EVAL/UNMAKE sequence for the nullmove is never done, but the nullmove is promoted to the head of the sorted list. Then in the recursion phase, MAKE / CONTINUE / UNMAKE is done on the nullmove, and the PV from the null becomes the first move in all normal continuations, if it was one of the moves on offer.

return_nullmove

public boolean return_nullmove
if return_nullmove is true, nullmove will be part of the normal result and may be returned at top level. If you actually receive a "nullmove" as the principle variation, it means there's no way to improve your position within the search depth.

allow_alpha_beta

public boolean allow_alpha_beta
if true, alpha beta will be used to prune the search tree. This is always good unless the result of the search is being randomized. If alpha beta is used, all but the first element in the result have unreliable evaluations, so randomization of the "first few" results is not meaningful.

allow_good_enough

public boolean allow_good_enough
normally, the search continues to slog on until the best move is found. "good enough" cutoffs stop when a certain threshold is reached. used safely, this threshold would be the value of a winning move, so the search would stop with a winning move but not necessarily the best winning move.

allow_killer

public boolean allow_killer
killer heuristic tries to borrow the evaluations of "first cousin" nodes that have already been evaluated. 
             (a)
      (b)        (c)
    (d1)(d2)..    (e1)(e2)...
the general idea is that e1, e2.. are similar to d1, d2.. so the best choices in the "d" series are also the best choices in the "e" series. Alha beta works better if the best choices are tried first. This depends on same_move_p recognising the e's as the same moves as the d's

allow_best_killer

public boolean allow_best_killer
alternative to allow_killer, allow_best_killer promotes only the best of the cousin nodes to be investigated first

Static_Evaluate_Move

public double Static_Evaluate_Move(commonMove mm)
this is used to statically evaluate one move from a list of legal moves. For each move in the list, Make_Move/Static_Eval/UnMake_Move is performed and the evaluations are saved. CommonDriver.eval_clock is incremented just before each Make_Move/Static_Eval/UnMake_Move sequence.

It's a useful debugging technique to record the current eval_clock in all moves, as part of your RobotProtocol.Static_Evaluate_Position(online.game.commonMove) method. then if certain moves come to your attention (for example, the bad move that was actually chosen) you can look for that eval state on a duplicate run.

Because conditional breakpoints can be quite slow, the variable CommonDriver.stop_at_eval_clock is available. When the clock reaches the specified value, RobotProtocol.Search_Break(java.lang.String) is called where you can put an unconditional breakpoint.

Parameters:
mm -
Returns:
a value for the move

Find_Static_Best_Move

public commonMove Find_Static_Best_Move(int randomn,
                                        double dif)
this is the main entry point to perform a search. From here, the search driver will call List_Of_Legal_Moves Make_Move Unmake_Move and Static_Evaluate_Position as needed, and will eventually produce an evaluated list of top level moves.

If "randomn" is not zero, then up to that number of moves are skipped unless the difference from the best move evaluation is more than dif

Parameters:
randomn - the number of potential moves to randomize
dif - the difference in evaluation from the best to stop randomizing
Returns:
a move selected as next
